Docker Images and Containers (Detailed Explanation)

Understanding the difference between Docker Images and Docker Containers is one of the most important Docker concepts.

What is a Docker Image?

A Docker Image is a read-only template that contains everything needed to run an application.

It includes:

Application code
Runtime (Java, Python, Node.js, etc.)
Libraries
Dependencies
Environment variables
Configuration files
Default startup command (CMD or ENTRYPOINT)

Think of an image as a blueprint or template.

Example
Nginx Image

+-------------------------+
| Ubuntu OS               |
| Nginx Installed          |
| Configuration Files      |
| Libraries               |
| CMD: nginx              |
+-------------------------+

An image cannot be modified while it is running. To change it, you typically rebuild a new image.

What is a Docker Container?

A Docker Container is a running instance of a Docker image.

When Docker starts an image:

It creates a writable layer on top of the image.
It starts the application defined by CMD or ENTRYPOINT.

Think of a container as a running process created from an image.

Example:

Image
   |
   +----> Container 1
   |
   +----> Container 2
   |
   +----> Container 3

One image can create multiple containers.

Real-World Analogy
Blueprint (Image)
       |
       | Build
       ↓
House (Container)

Or:

Class (Image)
      |
      ↓
Object (Container)
Image vs Container
Docker Image	Docker Container
Read-only template	Running instance
Cannot execute by itself	Executes applications
Created from Dockerfile	Created from an image
Can create many containers	Runs one application/process
Stored locally or in registries	Runs on the Docker host
